# Chapter 2: Module 2: Building Blocks of React - Components and JSX

## Module 2: Building Blocks of React - Components and JSX

React is built around the concept of **components**—self-contained, reusable pieces of code that manage their own state and render UI. These components are the foundation of every React application, and they communicate with each other using **props** (short for properties). In this chapter, we’ll explore how to create and manage React components using **JSX**, the syntax extension that makes writing React a joy.

By the end of this module, you’ll understand the difference between functional and class components, learn how to write and render components with JSX, use props to pass data between components, and grasp the concept of the **virtual DOM** and its benefits.

---

## What Are React Components?

A React **component** is a reusable piece of UI that can be composed with other components to build complex interfaces. Think of components like LEGO bricks: each brick is a small, functional unit, and together they form a larger structure.

There are two primary types of components in React:

1. **Functional Components**
2. **Class Components**

Both serve the same purpose—rendering UI—but they differ in syntax, capabilities, and how they manage state and lifecycle.

### Functional Components

Functional components are JavaScript functions that return JSX. They are simpler and more concise than class components and are now the **recommended** way to write components in modern React (especially with the introduction of **Hooks** in React 16.8).

```jsx
function Welcome() {
  return <h1>Hello, React!</h1>;
}
```

> ✅ Functional components are lightweight, easier to read, and perform better than class components in most cases.

### Class Components

Class components are ES6 classes that extend `React.Component` and must include a `render()` method that returns JSX. They were the primary way to manage state and lifecycle in React before Hooks.

```jsx
import React from 'react';

class Welcome extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <h1>Hello, React!</h1>;
  }
}
```

> ⚠️ Class components are still supported but are considered legacy in favor of functional components with Hooks.

---

## Introducing JSX

JSX stands for **JavaScript XML**—it’s a syntax extension that allows you to write HTML-like code directly inside JavaScript. This makes component definitions more intuitive and readable.

> 💡 JSX is not valid JavaScript on its own. It must be transformed into regular JavaScript by tools like **Babel** before running in the browser.

### Writing Components with JSX

Let’s create a simple `Greeting` component that displays a welcome message.

```jsx
function Greeting() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to My App</h1>
      <p>This is your first React component!</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This component returns a `<div>` containing an `<h1>` and a `<p>`. Notice how we use parentheses `()` around the JSX to make it readable across multiple lines.

### Embedding JavaScript in JSX

You can embed JavaScript expressions inside JSX using curly braces `{}`.

```jsx
function Greeting({ name, age }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>
      <p>You are {age} years old.</p>
      <p>Next year, you will be {age + 1}.</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Here, `name` and `age` are passed as **props** to the component. The expressions inside `{}` are evaluated and rendered as text.

> 🔁 Important: Only expressions are allowed inside `{}`. Statements like `if` or `for` won't work directly.

---

## Props: Passing Data Between Components

In React, **props** (short for properties) are read-only inputs to components. They allow parent components to pass data down to child components.

Props are similar to function arguments—they let components be dynamic and reusable.

### Example: User Profile Component

Let’s create a `UserProfile` component that displays user information passed via props.

```jsx
function UserProfile({ username, bio, avatar }) {
  return (
    <div className="user-profile">
      <img src={avatar} alt={username} className="avatar" />
      <h2>{username}</h2>
      <p>{bio}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now, we can use this component in a parent component like so:

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <UserProfile
        username="Alex Johnson"
        bio="Frontend Developer | React Enthusiast"
        avatar="https://example.com/avatar.png"
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

> ✅ Props are immutable. A component should never modify its own props.

---

## The Virtual DOM and Why It Matters

One of React’s most powerful features is the **Virtual DOM**—a lightweight in-memory representation of the real DOM.

### How the DOM Works (Without React)

In traditional web development, when you update the UI, the browser re-renders the entire page, recalculates styles, and repaints the screen. This process is called **reflow** and **repaint**, and it can be slow, especially with complex UIs.

### How React Uses the Virtual DOM

React creates a **Virtual DOM** (a JavaScript object) that mirrors the real DOM. When data changes:

1. React updates the Virtual DOM.
2. It compares the updated Virtual DOM with a previous version (**diffing algorithm**).
3. It calculates the minimal set of changes needed (**reconciliation**).
4. It applies only those changes to the real DOM.

This process is called **diffing** and **reconciliation**, and it ensures only the necessary parts of the page are updated—dramatically improving performance.

> 🚀 Example: Imagine a list of 1000 items. If one item changes, React updates only that item in the DOM instead of re-rendering all 1000.

This is why React is so fast and efficient, even with complex, dynamic UIs.

---

