# Chapter 5: Module 5: Working with APIs and Asynchronous Data

## Working with APIs and Asynchronous Data

In modern web development, fetching and managing external data is a fundamental skill. React applications often interact with RESTful APIs, GraphQL endpoints, or other data sources to provide dynamic content. In this chapter, we’ll explore how to handle asynchronous operations in React, make HTTP requests using popular libraries, and manage loading and error states effectively.

By the end, you’ll be able to confidently integrate external data into your React apps—whether it's a simple user list or a complex dashboard.

---

## Making HTTP Requests in React

React itself doesn’t include built-in tools for making HTTP requests, so we rely on external libraries or the native `fetch` API. Two of the most popular options are:

- **`fetch`**: Native browser API, lightweight, no dependencies.
- **`axios`**: Third-party library with a more feature-rich API, automatic JSON parsing, and better error handling.

Let’s compare both approaches.

---

### Using `fetch`

The `fetch` API is built into modern browsers and returns a Promise that resolves to the `Response` object. You typically chain `.then()` calls or use `async/await` for cleaner code.

#### Basic Example: Fetching a User List

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function UserList() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchUsers = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users');
        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
        }
        const data = await response.json();
        setUsers(data);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchUsers();
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <p>Loading users...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

> ✅ **Pros**: No extra dependencies, standard across browsers.
> ❌ **Cons**: Manual error checking, no interceptors, less convenient syntax.

---

### Using `axios`

Axios simplifies HTTP requests with a cleaner API and automatic JSON parsing.

#### Install Axios

```bash
npm install axios
```

#### Example: Fetching Posts with Axios

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

function PostList() {
  const [posts, setPosts] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchPosts = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await axios.get('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts');
        setPosts(response.data);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };

    fetchPosts();
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <p>Loading posts...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      {posts.map(post => (
        <article key={post.id}>
          <h3>{post.title}</h3>
          <p>{post.body}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

> ✅ **Pros**: Automatic JSON parsing, better error handling, supports request/response interceptors.
> ❌ **Cons**: Adds a dependency to your project.

> 💡 **Tip**: Consider creating a custom `apiClient.js` file to centralize your HTTP configuration (base URL, headers, timeouts).

```js
// apiClient.js
import axios from 'axios';

const apiClient = axios.create({
  baseURL: 'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com',
  timeout: 10000,
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
  },
});

export default apiClient;
```

Now use `apiClient.get('/users')` throughout your app.

---

## Handling Asynchronous Operations with `async/await`

Modern JavaScript uses `async/await` to write asynchronous code that looks synchronous, improving readability and maintainability.

### Key Concepts

- `async` functions always return a Promise.
- `await` pauses execution until the Promise resolves.
- Errors are caught using `try/catch`.

```js
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    const result = await someAsyncFunction();
    console.log(result);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed:", error);
  }
}
```

> 🔁 Always handle errors—network requests can fail due to timeouts, invalid URLs, or server issues.

---

## Managing Loading and Error States

User experience improves when your app clearly communicates what’s happening:

- **Loading**: Show a spinner or placeholder.
- **Success**: Render the data.
- **Error**: Display a user-friendly message.

### Pattern: Loading → Success → Error

```jsx
function DataComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState({
    data: null,
    loading: true,
    error: null,
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    const loadData = async () => {
      try {
        setState(prev => ({ ...prev, loading: true, error: null }));
        const response = await axios.get('/api/data');
        setState({ data: response.data, loading: false, error: null });
      } catch (err) {
        setState({ data: null, loading: false, error: err.message });
      }
    };

    loadData();
  }, []);

  if (state.loading) return <Spinner />;
  if (state.error) return <ErrorMessage message={state.error} />;
  if (!state.data) return null;

  return <DataView data={state.data} />;
}
```

This pattern is reusable and keeps your component clean.

---

## Using `useReducer` for Complex State Logic

When state logic becomes complex—with multiple sub-states, transitions, or derived data—`useState` can feel limiting. The `useReducer` hook offers a more structured way to manage state, inspired by Redux.

### When to Use `useReducer`

- State has multiple related sub-values.
- Next state depends on the previous one.
- You want to extract state logic into a reducer function.

### Example: Fetching with `useReducer`

```jsx
import { useReducer, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

const initialState = {
  data: null,
  loading: false,
  error: null,
};

function reducer(state, action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'FETCH_INIT':
      return { ...state, loading: true, error: null };
    case 'FETCH_SUCCESS':
      return { ...state, loading: false, data: action.payload };
    case 'FETCH_FAILURE':
      return { ...state, loading: false, error: action.payload };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchUser = async () => {
      dispatch({ type: 'FETCH_INIT' });
      try {
        const response = await axios.get(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/${userId}`);
        dispatch({ type: 'FETCH_SUCCESS', payload: response.data });
      } catch (err) {
        dispatch({ type: 'FETCH_FAILURE', payload: err.message });
      }
    };

    fetchUser();
  }, [userId]);

  if (state.loading) return <p>Loading profile...</p>;
  if (state.error) return <p>Error: {state.error}</p>;
  if (!state.data) return null;

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{state.data.name}</h2>
      <p>Email: {state.data.email}</p>
      <p>Phone: {state.data.phone}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

> 📌 **Benefits of `useReducer`**:
> - Centralizes state logic.
> - Easier to debug with actions and state history.
> - Scales well for complex UIs.

